"Hu Y., Zhou C., Liu J.","Observational evidence for poleward expansion of the Hadley circulation",2011,"Advances in Atmospheric Sciences","28","1",,"33","44",,,10.1007/s00376-010-0032-1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78650675347&partnerID=40&md5=adbe462d33fd0457d71e3dea3efec75e","Department of Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences, School of Physics, Peking University, Beijing 100871, China; State Key Laboratory of Numerical Modeling for Atmospheric Sciences and Geophysical Fluid Dynamics, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Beijing 100029, China; Laboratory for Climate and Ocean-Atmosphere Studies, Peking University, Beijing 100871, China","Hu, Y., Department of Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences, School of Physics, Peking University, Beijing 100871, China, Laboratory for Climate and Ocean-Atmosphere Studies, Peking University, Beijing 100871, China; Zhou, C., Department of Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences, School of Physics, Peking University, Beijing 100871, China; Liu, J., State Key Laboratory of Numerical Modeling for Atmospheric Sciences and Geophysical Fluid Dynamics, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Beijing 100029, China","How the Hadley circulation changes in response to global climate change and how its change impacts upon regional and global climates has generated a lot of interest in the literature in the past few years. In this paper, consistent and statistically significant poleward expansion of the Hadley circulation in the past few decades is demonstrated, using independent observational datasets as proxy measures of the Hadley circulation. Both observational outgoing longwave radiation and precipitation datasets show an annual average total poleward expansion of the Hadley cells of about 3.6° latitude. Sea level pressure from observational and reanalysis datasets show smaller magnitudes of poleward expansion, of about 1.2° latitude. Ensemble general circulation model simulations forced by observed time-varying sea surface temperatures were found to generate a total poleward expansion of about 1.23° latitude. Possible mechanisms behind the changes in the horizontal extent of the Hadley circulation are discussed. © 2010 Chinese National Committee for International Association of Meteorology and Atmospheric Sciences, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Science Press and Springer-Verlag Berlin Heidelberg.","climate change; Hadley circulation; outgoing longwave radiation; precipitation; sea level pressure",,,,,,,"Adler, R.F., The Version 2 Global Precipitation Climatology Project (GPCP) Monthly Precipitation Analysis (1979-Present) (2003) J. Hydrometeor., 4, pp. 1147-1167; Allan, R.J., Ansell, T.J., A new globally complete monthly historical mean sea level pressure data set (HadSLP2): 1850-2004 (2006) J. Climate, 19, pp. 5816-5842; Chen, J.Y., Carlson, B.E., del Genio, A.D., Evidence for strengthening of the tropical general circulation in the 1990s (2002) Science, 295, pp. 838-841; Chen, G., Held, I.M., Phase speed spectra and the recent poleward shift of Southern Hemisphere surface westerlies (2007) Geophys. Res. Lett., 34, pp. L21805; Chen, G., Lu, J., Frierson, D.M.W., Phase speed spectra and the latitude of surface westerlies: Interannual variability and global warming trend (2008) J. Climate, 21, pp. 5942-5959; Frierson, D.M.W., Lu, J., Chen, G., The width of the Hadley cell in simple and comprehensive general circulation models (2007) Geophys. Res. Lett., 34, pp. L18804; Fu, Q., Johanson, C.M., Wallace, J.M., Reichler, T., Enhanced mid-latitude tropospheric warming in satellite measurements (2006) Science, 312, p. 1179; Held, I.M., The general circulation of the atmosphere (2000) Proc. 2000 Program in Geophysical Fluid Dynamics, pp. 1-54. , http://gfd.whoi.edu, Woods Hole, MA: Woods Hole Oceanographic Institute, Available online at; Held, I.M., Hou, A.Y., Nonlinear axially symmetric circulations in a nearly inviscid atmosphere (1980) J. Atmos. Res., 37, pp. 515-533; Hu, Y., Fu, Q., Observed polew